d the ongoing efforts of the Russian government to boost local pharmaceutical innovation, which in turn produced a now widely shared vision of an independent and self-sufficient nation. The resulting industrial organizations and practices, she argues, came to embed and transmit particular imaginaries of the nation and its future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPharmaceutical industryxPolitical aspectszRussia (Federation). 0aPharmaceutical industryxPolitical aspectszSoviet Union. 0aPharmaceutical industryzRussia (Federation)xHistory. 0aPharmaceutical industryzSoviet UnionxHistory. 4aArea Studies : Russian Studies. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479934423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479934/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles